title: For Sale:  LNIB S&W M&P .22 Full Size + 2 mags holster case paperwork
postcontent:
W/ two 12 round mags, BladeTech belt/paddle holster, case, paperwork.

Bought new April 2014, approx. 600 rounds.
Cleaned after every trip to the range, functions like new.
I am willing to meet at the NRA range if anyone wants to test fire it for themselves (bring your own ammo).

Price includes two magazines (these guns are usually sold only with one) as well as a BladeTech holster that can be configured as either a paddle or belt holster. The BladeTech will also fit the M&P 9 or 40 as well. The extra magazine cost me $30 and the holster was another $50.

Good gun for beginning shooter or as a trainer for any centerfire strike-fired pistol.
Grip is slim and fits most hands, trigger light and crisp and aluminum slide is easy to rack.
Easy to clean, no tools required to disassemble.

Mag release is ambidextrous (currently set for right handed shooters) and barrel is threaded for a suppressor. Tools for both are included.

Please contact me if you would like to see more pictures or if you have any questions.
Please bring your VA Driver's License and VA CHP with you. Thank you!

If you live in another state I am happy to ship to your local FFL but please note that the 12 round magazines and threaded barrel make this gun illegal to ship to states such as California.

Edit: I have received several questions from people asking why a CHP (Concealed Handgun Permit) is necessary. We live in a litigious society and I do not want to sell to a potential felon, whack job or ATF agent. Therefore I kindly request that you bring your CHP, or military/LEO ID to verify that you are not a prohibited person.

If you don't have anything like that, simply drop by your local police station and ask them for a printout of your criminal record. I've done this myself and it takes only a couple of minutes (I'll throw in a couple of boxes of ammo for your time).

I do apologize for any inconvenience this may cause, but let's remember there are people out there who work tirelessly to take away your right to self defense who would just love to use Armslist sales as an excuse for pushing universal background checks and gun registration. Let's not give them any ammo.

title: For Trade:  Magnum Research Lone Eagle in 308 Single Shot**TRADE PENDING**
postcontent:
A true hand canon in 308. The Lone Eagle features a rotary breechblock similar to those found in artillery. This design provided enormous strong lockup.
Overall length is seventeen inches. Barrel is heavily ported. This hand canon fires a 7.62x51 or 308 round. It is a single shot action. Once the round is in the breech, the firearm is cocked using the cocking lever on the front of the grip. It also has a locking safety button. The grip is very comfortable. 
The scope is a Leupold M-8 x 4 with extended eye relief. Mounted on rail, that can be moved to suit the individuals preference. 
These firearms were indeed ridiculously overbuilt. With the strong lockup and heavy barrel these very well known for their extreme accuracy. With a five shot group at 75 yards, even I was able to shoot a half dollar size group.
It was indeed fun to see  five-foot muzzle flames, and a deafening concussion that may require double hearing protection. Others at the range were indeed impressed every time I fired the firearm. 
If you desire at any time in the future you wish to change barrels they can be found.

title: For Sale:  M1917 Enfield
postcontent: The U.S. made Enfield was produced during WW1 at first for the UK in 303 British (p14) but, when American decided to go kick some European butt we chambered the same rifle in 30-06 Springfield. Thus the great Enfield .30 cal was born. It was the rifle that was the most produced and used in WW1. An M1917 Enfield rifle was used by Sergeant Alvin York on October 8, 1918, that would see him awarded the Medal of Honor. A true awesome piece of American history. This one was made by Remington and is in great firering condition

postcontent:
Up for sale or trade is a Walther PPQ M1 chambered in 9mm.  It comes with one 15 round magazine and one 18 round magazine, a Walther pistol case, small, medium, and large backstraps (which are NOT marked RFID), and the owner’s manual.  I am not the original owner, so I do not know the round count.  I have only put one 50 rd box of Winchester White Box through it. When I bought the gun, it only came with the pistol, the two magazines, and the medium backstrap.  It wasn’t until I got home that I realized that the roll pin that holds the backstrap in place was also missing.   I screwed up and paid the guy too much for the gun.  So, after ordering the replacement backstraps, the roll pin, owner’s manual, and pistol case, I have $570 into this.  I know I can’t get that much for it, but I am asking $525 cash price.  For trades, I am interested in mainly Sig’s, specifically the P226 , SP2022, or P320, but I am open to other offers.  Let me know what you have.   I am located in Hampton.

Buyers must be 21 years of age or older and either Virginia residents or active duty military stationed in Virginia on PCS orders.  Buyers must be willing to sign a bill of sale and present two forms of government issued ID to include a Virginia driver’s license and CCW permit or Voter Registration to show you are not a felon.  For military, I will need to see your military ID along with your PCS orders showing you are stationed in Virginia if you are not a Virginia resident.

P.S. The trigger is phenomenal on this gun.  If I wasn’t already so heavily invested on my other carry setup, I would probably keep it.

title: For Sale:  Kahr cw380 1 mag and IWB holster
postcontent:
This gun is less than a year old with less than 200 rounds through it. I used it as my EDC. The holster is a Flashbang-Ava holster (this holster works for men too). It's a great carry piece, and is fun to shoot.

The CW380 pistol has a 2.58 inch barrel, an overall length of 4.96 inches and a height of just 3.9 inches. It weighs just 10.2 ounces without a magazine. The pistol has a black polymer frame and features 4140 steel inserts molded into the front and back of the frame for added rigidity. It has a machined, solid 416 matte stainless steel slide and a textured polymer grip.

The Kahr CW380 features a lock breech, modified Browning type recoil lug, and utilizes Kahr's seven patents including the "safe cam" action found in all Kahr pistols. The result is a micro-compact pistol with very little recoil and quick follow-up shots. The pistol features drift adjustable white bar-dot combat rear sight and pinned-in polymer front sight.

Differences between the Kahr CW380 and Kahr P380 models include: the CW series has a conventional rifled barrel instead of the match grade polygonal barrel found on P models; the CW slide stop lever is MIM (metal-injection-molded) instead of machined; the CW series slide has fewer machining operations, and uses simple roll marking instead of engraved markings; the P380 comes with two magazines, but the CW series comes with one 6 rd steel magazine with flush baseplate. Lastly, the slide locks back after firing the last round – another feature missing on a number of other value-priced compact semi-auto pistols. The durability and reliability of the CW380 model makes it a strong consideration as a backup gun for law enforcement.

title: For Sale:  Kahr P380
postcontent:
Kahr P380 with Trijicon Night Sights 

Fantastic pocket pistol, this gun has had 250 rounds of ball ammo through it for break-in and 50 rounds of Hornady critical defense.  I purchased this gun for my wife in December of 2013 (at the height of the gun craze for $800).  Since she purse carries, the extremely small size isn't as important an issue for her.  She now prefers to carry a slightly larger CCW.  I have a P380 that I pocket carry, primarily use with shorts and a t-shirt in the summer time.  Absolutely love it, so small, so compact.  But, I don't need two.  Here are the stats:

- Locked breach browning type action
- 4.9" overall legnth
- 3.9" height
- .75" wide
- 2.53" premium Match Grade polygonal rifled Lothar-Walther barrel.
- Forged Stainless steel slide.
- Polymer frame with integral stainless steel rails
- About 11 ounces in weight
- Dovetail Trijicon front & rear night sights
- Manual slide lock
- Striker fired
- Pachmayr slip-on grip sleeve
- (2) 6 round magazines

If you don't know the difference from the P380 and the CW380 let me inform you.  The P series of Kahr pistols is their "premium" line and the CW series is the budget line.  Some of the differences are:

- P380 has a match grade barrel, CW380 has a NON MATCH conventionally rifled barrel (I can tell you that this pistol is ridiculously accurate, way more accurate than I can be.  Not that is means much, in a life/death situation, but I can easily put rounds on a steel silhouette target from 100 yards)
- The P380 has laser cut markings vs. the roll marks of the CW380
- The P380 has more refined contours compared to the more basic Slide machining contours of the CW380
- The P380 comes with premium front/rear trijicon night sights compared to the basic sights of the CW380
- The slide release, takedown lever, etc are Forged parts on the P380 compared to (MIM) metal injected mold parts on the CW380

Don't hesitate to text for additional pictures or questions. 8six5-3six8-2six52.  Cash only, only trade I would entertain would be a Glock 42 and some boot.
